Subject: [PATCH 5/6] ggml-cuda: TurboQuant TQ3_0 / TQ4_0 CUDA core kernels

Target: PrismML-Eng/llama.cpp tag prism-b9596-9fcaed7, after patches 0001-0004.

Clean-room CUDA implementation of the TurboQuant KV-cache types (no code from
the unlicensed community CUDA gist):

- turboquant.cuh (new): device-side codebooks (identical constants to the CPU
  reference in ggml-quants.c), sign mask (bit-packed form of the golden-ratio
  hash table), scalar per-thread block quantizer (RMS -> sign flips + WHT
  butterfly -> boundary scan, numerically identical algorithm to the CPU
  reference), per-element closed-form dequantizer
  y[j] = d/sqrt(32) * sign[j] * sum_k (-1)^popc(j&k) * C[idx_k]
  (equal to the inverse-RHT butterfly; validated host-side by
  vendor/run_kernel_tests.py stage 4), and bit-exact code unpack helpers.
- convert.cu: dequantize-rows kernels (contiguous + non-contiguous), one warp
  per 32-block via a 5-stage __shfl_xor_sync Walsh-Hadamard butterfly; wired
  into to_fp16 / to_fp32 / to_fp16_nc / to_fp32_nc dispatch. The fp16 paths
  are what flash attention's prefill (MMA/tile) route uses for a quantized V.
- set-rows.cu: KV-write path — f32 -> TQ3_0/TQ4_0 rows via set_rows_cuda_quant
  (block-32 layout byte-identical to the CPU kernels).
- ggml-cuda.cu: allow TQ3_0/TQ4_0 dst in GGML_OP_SET_ROWS supports_op.

Not wired (documented in suiban/vendor/README.md): GGML_OP_CPY f32<->TQ (this
fork writes the KV cache through SET_ROWS; unsupported ops fall back to the
CPU backend, which has full TQ support) and the bf16 convert paths.
---
